This profile report is an aggregation of an Oracle extended SQL trace file that accounts for 0.109924 seconds.

You can think of this report as an invoice explaining how your time was spent, with call counts and durations acting as quantities and prices. It will help you answer the four most important questions about an application’s performance:

  • How long did this end-user experience take?
  • Why did it consume the time that it did?
  • What if you change something? How would a proposed change impact the duration of this experience?
  • What else could you do to reduce the duration of this experience? Is the program efficient?

However, this report can answer these questions only if the duration of the trace file on which it is based matches the duration of the experience you want to investigate. If your end-user experience did not last 0.109924 seconds, then consult the following resources:

  • The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 9 “Trace File Time Scoping” (available from the Method R Workbench Help menu)
  • Optimizing Oracle Performance chapter 3 “Targeting the Right Diagnostic Data”
  • Method R Trace, a zero-click high-precision trace file collector for Oracle SQL Developer

The advisory paragraphs that accompany the data in this document are meant to enhance your interpretation of the data. In cases where they run afoul of sound judgment, please open a case with Method R Support .

4.1.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 3w165fw0gmbtp was dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” and “CPU: FETCH dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls have consumed 46.2% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls. Parsing too often prevents an application from scaling to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system might happen to have, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses (that is, prepares) a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.1.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement 3w165fw0gmbtp touched the database buffer cache twenty-nine times and processed three rows, an average of 9.67 LIOs per row. The statement used the buffer cache efficiently.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to return many rows per “FETCH” call, but this application returns an average of only 1.00 row per “FETCH” call.

The statement obtained zero Oracle blocks from OS read calls, which means that your kernel process found the block it needed in the database buffer cache on 100.0% of buffer touches.

Parsing too often prevents an application from scaling to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system might happen to have, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses (that is, prepares) a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.3.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement 2syvqzbxp4k9z touched the database buffer cache twenty-three times but processed no rows, an average of 5.75 LIOs per “EXEC” call. The statement is efficient only if it joins three or more base tables, or if it is an aggregation.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to accomplish everything this statement does with just one “PARSE” call, but the application has executed four “PARSE” calls for this statement. Eliminating unnecessary “PARSE” calls should improve the total experience duration by at least 0.000340 seconds.

4.4.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 5pnxt7ap1kvc0 was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls have consumed 120.6% of the statement duration. These are high-productivity calls that you want to see dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application executing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls than necessary. The Profile by Database Call section will help you understand whether the application is using the Oracle Database efficiently.
  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls have consumed −24.9% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls. A small number of long-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls likely identifies a trace file collection error; for example, when tracing has been disabled before a recursive SQL statement has completed. A large number of short-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls implies that your process has been frequently preempted by the operating system. You can corroborate the preemption hypothesis by observing high overall system CPU utilization and high paging or swapping rates. Fix the problem by optimizing your program’s CPU consumption (and the programs it competes against for CPU time). Eliminate unnecessary “PARSE” calls, process data in sets instead of row-by-row, and ensure that your SQL visits the fewest database blocks that it can.

4.7.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement gngtvs38t0060 was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls have consumed 63.7% of the statement duration. These are high-productivity calls that you want to see dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application executing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls than necessary. The Profile by Database Call section will help you understand whether the application is using the Oracle Database efficiently.
  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls have consumed 20.8% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls. Parsing too often prevents an application from scaling to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system might happen to have, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses (that is, prepares) a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.7.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement gngtvs38t0060 touched the database buffer cache four times but processed no rows, an average of 2.00 LIOs per “EXEC” call. The statement used the buffer cache efficiently.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  1. SELECT /*+ CONNECT_BY_FILTERING */ s.privilege#
  2. FROM sys.sysauth$ s CONNECT BY s.grantee# = PRIOR s.privilege#
  3. AND (s.privilege# > 0
  4. OR s.privilege# = -352) START WITH (s.privilege# > 0

  7. FROM sys.codeauth$ c1
  8. WHERE c1.obj# = :1)
  9. UNION
  10. SELECT c2.privilege#
  11. FROM sys.codeauth$ c2
  12. WHERE c2.obj# = :2
  13. ORDER BY 1 ASC

The statement is a query that returned seventeen rows. Any time a query returns more than ten rows, it signals a potential opportunity for an application design improvement. If the query’s output is being displayed for a user to see, consider that people are normally not interested in seeing more than ten rows at once [Tow-Millsap law]. If the query is feeding an application for summarization or joining, consider doing such work in SQL or PL/SQL within the database where the processing can be vastly more efficient.

4.10.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 03guhbfpak0w7 was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls”, “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”, and “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls have consumed 45.0% of the statement duration. These are high-productivity calls that you want to see dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application executing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls than necessary. The Profile by Database Call section will help you understand whether the application is using the Oracle Database efficiently.
  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls have consumed 29.2% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls. Parsing too often prevents an application from scaling to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system might happen to have, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses (that is, prepares) a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.
  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls have consumed 21.5% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls. A small number of long-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls likely identifies a trace file collection error; for example, when tracing has been disabled before a recursive SQL statement has completed. A large number of short-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls implies that your process has been frequently preempted by the operating system. You can corroborate the preemption hypothesis by observing high overall system CPU utilization and high paging or swapping rates. Fix the problem by optimizing your program’s CPU consumption (and the programs it competes against for CPU time). Eliminate unnecessary “PARSE” calls, process data in sets instead of row-by-row, and ensure that your SQL visits the fewest database blocks that it can.

4.10.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement 03guhbfpak0w7 touched the database buffer cache twenty-one times and processed five rows, an average of 4.20 LIOs per row. The statement used the buffer cache efficiently.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to accomplish everything this statement does with just one “PARSE” call, but the application has executed four “PARSE” calls for this statement. Eliminating unnecessary “PARSE” calls should improve the total experience duration by at least −0.000083 seconds.
  • It should be possible to return many rows per “FETCH” call, but this application returns an average of only 0.71 rows per “FETCH” call.

The statement obtained zero Oracle blocks from OS read calls, which means that your kernel process found the block it needed in the database buffer cache on 100.0% of buffer touches.

4.14.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 7fwkap81p3xjr was dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls have consumed 99.3% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls. 4.15.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 9babjv8yq8ru3 was dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls” and “SQL*Net message from client” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for between calls” calls have consumed 50.8% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls” calls. A small number of long-duration “unaccounted-for between calls” calls likely identifies a trace file collection error; for example, when tracing has been disabled for part of a user experience duration. A large number of short-duration “unaccounted-for between calls” calls implies that your process has been frequently preempted by the operating system. You can corroborate the preemption hypothesis by observing high overall system CPU utilization and high paging or swapping rates. Fix the problem by optimizing your program’s CPU consumption (and the programs it competes against for CPU time). Eliminate unnecessary “PARSE” calls, process data in sets instead of row-by-row, and ensure that your SQL visits the fewest database blocks that it can.
  • “SQL*Net message from client” calls have consumed 21.8% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by short-duration “SQL*Net message from client” calls. Each call indicates a network round trip. Eliminate unnecessary network round trips by eliminating unnecessary “PARSE” calls from your application, by processing data in sets instead of one row at a time, and by moving application logic into PL/SQL within the database.

4.18.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement fh5ufah919kun was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls have consumed 44.9% of the statement duration. These are high-productivity calls that you want to see dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application executing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls than necessary. The Profile by Database Call section will help you understand whether the application is using the Oracle Database efficiently.
  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls have consumed 32.0% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls. A small number of long-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls likely identifies a trace file collection error; for example, when tracing has been disabled before a recursive SQL statement has completed. A large number of short-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls implies that your process has been frequently preempted by the operating system. You can corroborate the preemption hypothesis by observing high overall system CPU utilization and high paging or swapping rates. Fix the problem by optimizing your program’s CPU consumption (and the programs it competes against for CPU time). Eliminate unnecessary “PARSE” calls, process data in sets instead of row-by-row, and ensure that your SQL visits the fewest database blocks that it can.

4.20.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 9tt2m0mpc2qqp was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls”, “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”, and “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls have consumed 179.8% of the statement duration. These are high-productivity calls that you want to see dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application executing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls than necessary. The Profile by Database Call section will help you understand whether the application is using the Oracle Database efficiently.
  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls have consumed 20.8% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls. Parsing too often prevents an application from scaling to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system might happen to have, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses (that is, prepares) a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.
  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls have consumed −104.2% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls. A small number of long-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls likely identifies a trace file collection error; for example, when tracing has been disabled before a recursive SQL statement has completed. A large number of short-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls implies that your process has been frequently preempted by the operating system. You can corroborate the preemption hypothesis by observing high overall system CPU utilization and high paging or swapping rates. Fix the problem by optimizing your program’s CPU consumption (and the programs it competes against for CPU time). Eliminate unnecessary “PARSE” calls, process data in sets instead of row-by-row, and ensure that your SQL visits the fewest database blocks that it can.

4.33.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement bb055g46n0ccd was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” and “unaccounted-for between calls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls have consumed 62.9% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls. A small number of long-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls likely identifies a trace file collection error; for example, when tracing has been disabled before a recursive SQL statement has completed. A large number of short-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls implies that your process has been frequently preempted by the operating system. You can corroborate the preemption hypothesis by observing high overall system CPU utilization and high paging or swapping rates. Fix the problem by optimizing your program’s CPU consumption (and the programs it competes against for CPU time). Eliminate unnecessary “PARSE” calls, process data in sets instead of row-by-row, and ensure that your SQL visits the fewest database blocks that it can.
  • “unaccounted-for between calls” calls have consumed 21.8% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls” calls. Statement 83cq1aqjw5gmg was dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

4.47.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement PROF000000046 was dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for between calls” calls have consumed 84.6% of the statement duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls” calls. A small number of long-duration “unaccounted-for between calls” calls likely identifies a trace file collection error; for example, when tracing has been disabled for part of a user experience duration. A large number of short-duration “unaccounted-for between calls” calls implies that your process has been frequently preempted by the operating system. You can corroborate the preemption hypothesis by observing high overall system CPU utilization and high paging or swapping rates. Fix the problem by optimizing your program’s CPU consumption (and the programs it competes against for CPU time). Eliminate unnecessary “PARSE” calls, process data in sets instead of row-by-row, and ensure that your SQL visits the fewest database blocks that it can.
